# thinkpad-t14s — buying notes / consensus (Gen 6, 2025)
#
# config under consideration:
#   Lenovo ThinkPad T14s Gen 6, 14", Eclipse Black
#   Intel Core Ultra 7 255U (2.0 GHz)   ← NOTE: Arrow Lake-U, NOT Lunar Lake
#   32GB RAM (soldered LPDDR5x)
#   Intel integrated graphics (NOT Arc)
#   1TB SSD
#   14" WUXGA (1920x1200) display
#   WiFi 7 (802.11be), Bluetooth 5.4
#   3.08 lb (1.40 kg)
#   Windows 11 Pro
#
# consensus from reviews (Notebookcheck, PCWorld, XDA, Laptop Mag,
# Tom's Hardware): a premium, durable, quiet, all-day work laptop with a
# great keyboard and a mediocre screen, at a price that's its main
# detractor. the 32GB/1TB/Intel spec is well chosen — especially for Linux.


# THE CHIP CAVEAT (read this first — it reframes the reviews)
#
# the 255U is Intel ARROW LAKE-U, not Lunar Lake. most of the glowing
# "21-hour battery / best T14s yet" press is about either the Lunar Lake
# V-series (256V/258V) or the Snapdragon model. don't transfer that hype
# to this chip.
#
#   255U (this config)   efficiency/value tier. 12 cores (2P+8E+2LP),
#                        plain "Intel Graphics" (NOT Arc 140V), and an
#                        NPU below 40 TOPS — so NOT Copilot+ certified.
#                        good, modest, cool-running. no generational
#                        leap over Meteor Lake.
#   256V/258V (Lunar)    the battery / iGPU / AI champion the headlines
#                        rave about. different chip.
#   Snapdragon X          longest battery, cheapest — but bad for Linux
#                        (see below). avoid if you run Linux.


# CONSENSUS PROS
#
# - build & ergonomics: classic ThinkPad. carbon-fiber / magnesium,
#   ~3.08 lb, best-in-class keyboard + TrackPoint, user-replaceable
#   keyboard. universally praised.
# - runs cool, quiet, and long vs earlier T14s gens. real-world ~11+ hrs
#   (a full workday); video playback into the high teens.
# - 32GB is the right call: Intel models use SOLDERED LPDDR5x, NOT
#   upgradeable. buying 32GB now is buying it forever. done correctly.
# - WiFi 7, good port selection, serviceable (replaceable) SSD, solid 1TB.


# CONSENSUS CONS
#
# - display is the weak point: WUXGA ~400 nits, anti-glare, but reviewers
#   consistently call the colors dull / lifeless. fine for work, not for
#   media or color work.
# - price: the recurring complaint. ~$1,500-1,880 depending on sale; some
#   say the Snapdragon model does most of the job for much less.
# - Arrow Lake-U is not a performance leap over Meteor Lake.


# LINUX ANGLE (the deciding factor for this repo's use)
#
# the Intel 255U is the RIGHT T14s to buy for Linux:
# - Intel iGPU + standard x86 = excellent kernel support out of the box.
# - AVOID the Snapdragon / ARM variant for Linux — support is still rough.
# - ThinkPads are among the best-supported Linux laptops generally; this
#   one is a clean target (soldered RAM aside).
# day-one Linux checklist lives in [[fedora-to-endeavouros]]; distro
# survey in [[arch-distros]]; Fedora specifics in [[fedora]].


# VS MY CURRENT LAPTOP — X1 CARBON 7th GEN (2019)
#
# current daily driver: ThinkPad X1 Carbon 7th Gen, 20QD001XUS
#   i7-8665U (4C/8T, 14nm Whiskey Lake-U), UHD Graphics 620
#   16GB soldered, 3840x2160 (4K) 16:9 display, ~2.4 lb (1.09 kg)
#   WiFi 5 (AC 9560), Ubuntu 24.04.4, kernel 6.17
#
#   axis        X1 Carbon 7th (current)     T14s Gen 6 (255U)        verdict
#   ----        -----------------------     -----------------        ------
#   CPU         i7-8665U 4C/8T (2019)       Ultra 7 255U 12C/14T     BIG WIN
#                                           (Arrow Lake-U, 2025)     ~2.5-3x
#                                                                    multi,
#                                                                    ~40-50%
#                                                                    single
#   RAM         16GB soldered (~5GB used)   32GB soldered            2x
#   battery     2019 cell, aging + 4K       ~11+ hrs, cool/quiet     BIG WIN
#   GPU         UHD 620 (Gen9.5)            Intel Graphics (Xe)      win
#   WiFi        WiFi 5 (AC 9560)            WiFi 7 (802.11be)        win
#   NPU         none                        yes, <40 TOPS            minor
#   display     3840x2160 4K, 16:9          1920x1200 WUXGA, 16:10   DOWNGRADE
#                                                                    (res) /
#                                                                    16:10 gain
#   weight      ~2.4 lb (1.09 kg)           3.08 lb (1.40 kg)        X1 WINS
#   build/kbd   premium carbon ThinkPad     premium carbon ThinkPad  wash
#
# the two trade-offs that aren't slam dunks:
#   1. resolution drops 4K -> WUXGA. on 14" 4K is arguably overkill and a
#      battery drain; T14s gains 16:10 (more vertical) + ~400 nits. but if
#      the 4K panel is precious to you, it's the one spec going backward.
#   2. the X1 is ~0.6 lb (270g) lighter.
#
# Linux: i'm on Ubuntu 24.04 / kernel 6.17 — already new enough for clean
# Arrow Lake-U support, so the 255U works out of the box. stick with Intel,
# not the Snapdragon variant.
#
# bottom line on the upgrade: a clear generational jump (CPU, RAM, battery,
# WiFi, GPU) after 6 years. only real costs are losing the 4K screen and
# gaining ~0.6 lb. easy yes unless the 4K panel is a dealbreaker.


# FINGERPRINT READER / DISPLAY OPTIONS (PSREF detail)
#
# from the official PSREF spec sheet (T14s Gen 6 Intel). these are
# configurable, so the exact panel/sensor depends on the SKU — confirm
# before buying.
#
# FINGERPRINT READER — two options only:
#   - touch-style fingerprint reader integrated in the POWER BUTTON,
#     match-on-chip (the print is matched on the sensor module, never
#     leaves it — good for security and for Linux)
#   - no fingerprint reader
#   => NOT guaranteed on every SKU (Lenovo offers a "no reader" build,
#      usually enterprise/special-bid), but present on virtually all
#      retail configs. the power button IS the reader.
#   Linux: power-button readers on recent ThinkPads generally work via
#   fprintd / libfprint (sudo + GNOME login unlock). Goodix sensors can
#   lag in support — verify against the exact sensor once in hand.
#   NOTE: IR camera for Windows Hello (facial) is OPTIONAL — probably not
#   on a base SKU, and irrelevant on Linux anyway.
#
# DISPLAY — "WUXGA" hides FOUR different 14" 1920x1200 panels, plus an
# OLED. the cheap base panel is the one reviewers call dull:
#   1. WUXGA 400nit, 45% NTSC, non-touch        <- base / "dull" panel,
#                                                  almost certainly what a
#                                                  base retail SKU ships
#   2. WUXGA 400nit, 45% NTSC, on-cell touch
#   3. WUXGA 500nit, 100% sRGB, non-touch (low power)   <- much better
#   4. WUXGA 500nit, 100% sRGB, 1500:1, Privacy Guard, on-cell touch
#   5. 2.8K (2880x1800) OLED, 120Hz VRR, 100% DCI-P3, touch  (Arrow Lake
#                                                             only)
#   => the earlier "dull / 45% NTSC" critique applies ONLY to panels 1-2.
#      coming from a 4K panel, confirm WHICH WUXGA the SKU has; if it's
#      the 45% NTSC one, price a Lenovo-direct build with panel 3 (500nit
#      100% sRGB) — it's the single biggest fixable compromise.
#   (2.8K OLED display is Arrow Lake only, per PSREF note.)
#
# PSREF: https://psref.lenovo.com/syspool/Sys/PDF/ThinkPad/ThinkPad_T14s_Gen_6_Intel/ThinkPad_T14s_Gen_6_Intel_Spec.pdf


# BOTTOM LINE
#
# good buy for a Linux work laptop if the price is acceptable and you
# don't need a great screen or Copilot+/Arc-class graphics. just calibrate
# expectations: the 255U is the sensible/value variant, not the
# Lunar-Lake battery/AI record-setter the headlines describe.


